    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-10-17T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-10-17T12:00:00-05:00" n="718"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d718">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">761.93/1698: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extract]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-10-17T20:00:00+03:00"
                            >October 17, 1940—8 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 11:40 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1361. In the course of a conversation with the Chinese Ambassador<note n="87"
                        xml:id="d718fn87">Shao Li-tzu.</note> this afternoon he stated that he had
                    again seen Vishinsky<note n="88" xml:id="d718fn88">Andrey Yanuaryevich
                        Vyshinsky, Soviet Vice Commissar for Foreign Affairs.</note> who in
                    reassuring him as to the continuance of Soviet aid to China had remarked that
                    “while the Soviet methods might have to undergo a change the Soviet goal
                    remained the same.”</p>
                <p>The Ambassador stated in so far as he was aware there had been no recent
                    appreciable diminution in Soviet aid to China but that on the other hand the
                    Soviet Government had not responded to his request for better types of airplanes
                    (see my 1235, September 25, 11 p.m.<note n="89" xml:id="d718fn89">Printed in
                        vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">iii</hi>, section under Union of Soviet Socialist
                        Republics entitled “Reports on Developments of Significance Concerning
                        Soviet Relations With Other Countries, Especially With the United
                        States.”</note>).</p>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
